  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 7.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Contrariwise",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " contrary to the line taken or to the view expressed by the severer portion of the community. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Rather",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word is omitted in A and B. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To forgive him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word is used of the mutual attitude of gracious forbearance which ought to exist among Christians(Forgiving one another,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ephesians 4:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Colossians 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), so that they might be not only Christians, but as Gentiles ignorantly called them, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Chrestians",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (\" kind-hearted,\" Ephesians 4:82). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And comfort",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"strengthen,\" \"encourage.\" The \"him\" is emitted in the Greek, with the same delicate, compassionate reticence which leads St. Paul to speak of this person \"a man of such of a kind.\" In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Galatians 6:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " St. Paul suddenly breaks off the course of his remarks to give similar advice in a tone of peculiar solemnity; and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Thessalonians 3:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he warns against any ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "excess",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the severity which he enjoins in the previous verse. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Such a one",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Like the indefinite \"one\" in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 5:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In the Greek it is compassionately placed last in the clause. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Should be swallowed up",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The same metaphor, of being swallowed in an abyss, occurs in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 15:54",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 5:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is said that Satan is ever striving to \"swallow up\" men. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "With overmuch sorrow;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "with the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "his, excessive grief",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Despair might drive the man to suicide, or apostasy, or the wretchlessness of unclean living. 2 Corinthians 2:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Forgive (χαρίσασθαι)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The idea of freeness (χάρις, see on Luke 1:30) lies in the word forgive, which is forth-give.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The idea of freeness (χάρις, see on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 1:30",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") lies in the word forgive, which is forth-give.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Overmuch sorrow (τῇπερισσοτέρᾳ λύπῃ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Rev. gives the force of the article, his sorrow. Overmuch, excessive, through the refusal of pardon. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]